Benign Prostatic Hyperplasia (BPH),Frequent urination; Nocturia; Weak urine stream; Hesitancy; Incomplete bladder emptying; Urinary urgency; Intermittent stream; Straining to urinate,Usually men >50 (common by 60-80),Ageing; Metabolic syndrome; Obesity; Diabetes (possible association); History of urinary retention
Prostatitis (general),Painful urination; Frequent urination; Urinary urgency; Pelvic/groin/genital pain; Low back pain; Fever (esp. acute bacterial),"Younger to middle-aged men (20-50), but can occur at any age",Recent urinary tract infection; STIs (in some cases); Prior urologic procedures; Immunosuppression
Acute Bacterial Prostatitis,High fever and chills; Severe urinary pain and burning; Frequent/urgent urination; Difficulty urinating; Perineal pain; Malaise,"Often younger and middle-aged adult men, but can occur at any age",Recent urinary tract infection; Instrumentation/catheterization; Diabetes; Urinary obstruction
Chronic Bacterial Prostatitis,Recurrent urinary tract infections; Pelvic discomfort; Painful ejaculation; Lower back or perineal pain; Dysuria; Intermittent fevers,Adults (often 30-50+),Recurrent UTIs; Prior acute bacterial prostatitis; Urinary tract abnormalities; Instrumentation
"Chronic Pelvic Pain Syndrome (Chronic Prostatitis, non-bacterial)",Chronic pelvic/perineal pain; Pain with ejaculation; Urinary frequency/urgency; Painful urination; Erectile dysfunction (sometimes),Younger to middle-aged men (20-50),Stress; Prior pelvic injury; History of urinary or genital infections (sometimes)
Asymptomatic Inflammatory Prostatitis,Often no symptoms; inflammation found incidentally on tests/biopsy,Middle-aged to older men (found on evaluation for other issues),Often detected on biopsy for elevated PSA; may co-occur with other prostatic conditions
Prostate Cancer,Often no early symptoms; Advanced disease: weak/interrupted urine flow; Hematuria or blood in semen; Pelvic or bone pain (metastasis); Unexplained weight loss; Erectile dysfunction,Mostly men >50 (average diagnosis ~65-70); uncommon <50,Age; Family history; African ancestry; BRCA1/2 or hereditary cancer syndromes; Obesity; High-fat diet (possible links)
Prostatic Intraepithelial Neoplasia (PIN),Usually asymptomatic (detected on biopsy); may be associated with elevated PSA,Middle-aged to older men,Associated with increased risk of prostate cancer; family history
Prostate Abscess,Fever; Chills; Severe perineal pain; Urinary retention or difficulty; Purulent urethral discharge (occasionally),"Adults, more common in middle-aged to older men",Diabetes mellitus (common risk factor); Immunosuppression; Chronic bacterial prostatitis; Urinary catheterization
Prostate Calculi (Prostatic Stones),Often asymptomatic; can cause chronic pelvic pain; Recurrent UTIs; Hematospermia; Lower urinary tract symptoms if obstructive,Middle-aged to older men,Chronic prostatitis; Recurrent infections; Prostatic duct obstruction
Prostate Cysts,Often asymptomatic; possible urinary obstruction; Pelvic pain if large; Recurrent infections,Any adult age; commonly found in middle-aged men,Congenital anomalies; Prior infections; Ductal obstruction
Granulomatous Prostatitis,Symptoms mimic prostatitis or prostate cancer: urinary frequency; Pelvic pain; Possible firm prostate on exam,Middle-aged to older men,Prior prostate procedures; Tuberculosis (if tuberculous granulomas); Other systemic granulomatous diseases
Atrophic Prostatitis,May be asymptomatic or have mild urinary symptoms; found on histology/biopsy,Older men,Age-related changes; often incidental finding
Xanthogranulomatous Prostatitis,Chronic urinary symptoms; Pelvic pain; May mimic carcinoma on exam/imaging,Middle-aged to older men,Chronic infection/inflammation; prior prostatic disease
